{"title_page": "HC Berkut", "text_new": "{{for|the original franchise established in 1997|HC Berkut-Kiev}}\n{{Infobox KHL team\n| team   = Berkut\n| colour      = #EE1B22\n| colour text = #FFFFFF\n| logo      =[[File:HCBerkut.png]]\n| name2   = '''HC Berkut'''\n* <small>'''HC Podil''' (2010\u201311)</small>\n* <small>'''HC Berkut''' (2004\u201310)</small>\n| nickname    = ''\"Golden Eagles\"''\n| founded     = 2004\n| folded   = 2013\n| city   = [[Brovary]]\n| arena      = [[Ice Arena TEC Terminal]]\n| capacity   = 1,500\n| league     = [[Professional Hockey League]]<br /><small>(2011\u20132013)</small>\n| division    = \n| colours  = {{color box|#EE1B22}} {{color box|#272264}} {{color box|white}}\n| uniform     =\n| owner       = {{flagicon|GEO}} [[David Zhvaniya]]\n| president   =\n| coach  =\n| captain     =\n| honors      =\n| affiliates  =\n| website     = [http://hc-berkut.com/ HC-Berkut.com]\n}}\n\n'''Berkut Hockey Club''' ({{lang-ua|\u0425\u041a \u0411\u0435\u0440\u043a\u0443\u0442}}, ''HC Berkut'') was a [[Ukraine|Ukrainian]] professional [[ice hockey]] team based in [[Brovary]]. While its home arena is in Brovary, within the [[Kiev oblast|Kiev region]], it also played in the city of [[Kiev]].\n\nIt was a founding member of the [[Professional Hockey League]] of Ukraine, before being expelled by the League and forfeited from the 2013 playoffs. The organization's current focus is its youth development program.\n\nThe team's name, Berkut, means [[golden eagle]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Financial dispute===\nThe team was expelled by the League and forfeited from the 2013 playoffs for not fulfilling its financial obligations to the League and to its players.<ref>http://isport.ua/hockey/ukraine/news/248042.html</ref><ref>http://isport.ua/hockey/ukraine/news/247165.html</ref><ref>http://hc-berkut.com/ru/articles/item/2013-03-05-milosh-holan-hotelos-byi-uznat-mnenie-mejdunarodnoy-federatsii-hokkeya</ref> Its former captain, [[Serhiy Klymentiev]], along with goaltender [[Igor Karpenko]] filed a lawsuit against the club at the conclusion of the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://isport.ua/hockey/ukraine/news/245817.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-05-31 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130510174811/http://isport.ua/hockey/ukraine/news/245817.html |archive-date=2013-05-10 |df= }}</ref> It has since not taken part in the [[2013\u201314 Ukrainian Hockey Championship]] season.\n\n===Name change===\nOn 26 January 2014, it was announced that HC Berkut-2, a Ukrainian ice hockey team in the Amateur Hockey League would be changing so as to avoid association with ''[[Berkut (special police forces)|Berkut]]'' forces in their role repressing [[Euromaidan]] activists.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://isport.ua/hockey/ukraine/news/281646.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2014-01-28 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140129043514/http://isport.ua/hockey/ukraine/news/281646.html |archive-date=2014-01-29 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==Players==\n\n===Team captains===\n* {{flagicon|Russia}} [[Roman Malov]] 2011 \u2013 2012\n* {{flagicon|UKR}} [[Serhiy Klymentiev]] 2012 \u2013 2013\n\n===Head coaches===\n* {{flagicon|UKR}} Dmytro Markovsky, 2011 \u2013 2012\n* {{flagicon|CZE}} [[Milo\u0161 Hola\u0148]], 2012 \u2013 present<ref>http://isport.ua/hockey/ukraine/news/204629.html</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080501153443/http://www.berkut.net.ua/ru/history.html Team History]\n\n{{Ukrainian Hockey Championships}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berkut, HC}}\n[[Category:Ice hockey teams in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Sport in Kiev]]\n[[Category:Sport in Brovary]]\n[[Category:Professional Hockey League teams]]\n\n\n{{Europe-icehockey-team-stub}}\n{{Ukraine-sport-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{for|the original franchise established in 1997|HC Berkut-Kiev}}\n{{Infobox KHL team\n| team   = Berkut\n| colour      = #EE1B22\n| colour text = #FFFFFF\n| logo      =[[File:HCBerkut.png]]\n| name2   = '''HC Berkut'''\n* <small>'''HC Podil''' (2010\u201311)</small>\n* <small>'''HC Berkut''' (2004\u201310)</small>\n| nickname    = ''\"Golden Eagles\"''\n| founded     = 2004\n| folded   = 2013\n| city   = [[Brovary]]\n| arena      = [[Ice Arena TEC Terminal]]\n| capacity   = 1,500\n| league     = [[Professional Hockey League]]<br /><small>(2011\u20132013)</small>\n| division    = \n| colours  = {{color box|#EE1B22}} {{color box|#272264}} {{color box|white}}\n| uniform     =\n| owner       = {{flagicon|GEO}} [[David Zhvaniya]]\n| president   =\n| coach  =\n| captain     =\n| honors      =\n| affiliates  =\n| website     = [http://hc-berkut.com/ HC-Berkut.com]\n}}\n\n'''Berkut Hockey Club''' ({{lang-ua|\u0425\u041a \u0411\u0435\u0440\u043a\u0443\u0442}}, ''HC Berkut'') was a [[Ukraine|Ukrainian]] professional [[ice hockey]] team based in [[Brovary]]. While its home arena is in Brovary, within the [[Kiev oblast|Kiev region]], it also played in the city of [[Kiev]].\n\nIt was a founding member of the [[Professional Hockey League]] of Ukraine, before being expelled by the League and forfeited from the 2013 playoffs. The organization's current focus is its youth development program.\n\nThe team's name, Berkut, means [[golden eagle]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Financial dispute===\nThe team was expelled by the League and forfeited from the 2013 playoffs over not fulfilling its financial obligations to the League and to its players.<ref>http://isport.ua/hockey/ukraine/news/248042.html</ref><ref>http://isport.ua/hockey/ukraine/news/247165.html</ref><ref>http://hc-berkut.com/ru/articles/item/2013-03-05-milosh-holan-hotelos-byi-uznat-mnenie-mejdunarodnoy-federatsii-hokkeya</ref> Its former captain, [[Serhiy Klymentiev]], along with goaltender [[Igor Karpenko]] filed a lawsuit against the club at the conclusion of the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://isport.ua/hockey/ukraine/news/245817.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-05-31 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130510174811/http://isport.ua/hockey/ukraine/news/245817.html |archive-date=2013-05-10 |df= }}</ref> It has since not taken part in the [[2013\u201314 Ukrainian Hockey Championship]] season.\n\n===Name change===\nOn 26 January 2014, it was announced that HC Berkut-2, a Ukrainian ice hockey team in the Amateur Hockey League would be changing so as to avoid association with ''[[Berkut (special police forces)|Berkut]]'' forces in their role repressing [[Euromaidan]] activists.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://isport.ua/hockey/ukraine/news/281646.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2014-01-28 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140129043514/http://isport.ua/hockey/ukraine/news/281646.html |archive-date=2014-01-29 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==Players==\n\n===Team captains===\n* {{flagicon|Russia}} [[Roman Malov]] 2011 \u2013 2012\n* {{flagicon|UKR}} [[Serhiy Klymentiev]] 2012 \u2013 2013\n\n===Head coaches===\n* {{flagicon|UKR}} Dmytro Markovsky, 2011 \u2013 2012\n* {{flagicon|CZE}} [[Milo\u0161 Hola\u0148]], 2012 \u2013 present<ref>http://isport.ua/hockey/ukraine/news/204629.html</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080501153443/http://www.berkut.net.ua/ru/history.html Team History]\n\n{{Ukrainian Hockey Championships}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berkut, HC}}\n[[Category:Ice hockey teams in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Sport in Kiev]]\n[[Category:Sport in Brovary]]\n[[Category:Professional Hockey League teams]]\n\n\n{{Europe-icehockey-team-stub}}\n{{Ukraine-sport-stub}}\n", "name_user": "This Works Too", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFinancial dispute", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HC_Berkut"}
{"title_page": "Global Energy Balance Network", "text_new": "{{Infobox organization\n| logo =\n| extinction = {{End date|November 30, 2015}}\n| type =non profit\n| purpose = front group for Coca-Cola <ref name=NYT><!-- excerpt=\u201cThe Global Energy Balance Network is nothing but a front group for Coca-Cola.\" - M. Nestle  -->http://well.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/08/09/coca-cola-funds-scientists-who-shift-blame-for-obesity-away-from-bad-diets/?_r=2</ref>\n| leader_title  = President<ref name=NYT />\n| leader_name   = [[James O. Hill]]\n| leader_title2 = Founder & Vice-President <ref name=NYT />\n| leader_name2  = [[Steven N. Blair]]\n| leader_name3  = [[Gregory A. Hand]]\n| leader_title3 = Founder<ref name=NYT />\n| name = Global Energy Balance Network\n| founded = {{Start date and age|2014}} at the [[University of Colorado]] and [[University of South Carolina]]\n| products = obesity research\n| owner = [[Coca-Cola]]\n| website = {{URL|gebn.org}} (was registered to Coca-Cola headquarters in Atlanta)<ref name=NYT />\n}}\nThe '''Global Energy Balance Network''' ('''GEBN''') was a US-based nonprofit claiming to fund research into causes of obesity, but was primarily known for promoting the idea that lack of exercise, not bad diet, was primarily responsible for the obesity epidemic. It has been characterised as an [[astroturfing]]<ref name=\"ChoiceFrontGroups\">{{cite web | url=https://www.choice.com.au/shopping/packaging-labelling-and-advertising/advertising/articles/front-groups-and-astroturfing | title=Front groups and 'astroturfing' | publisher=[[Choice (Australian consumer organisation)|Choice]] | accessdate=October 11, 2015}}</ref> organisation. It received substantial funding from [[Coca-Cola]].<ref name=\"NYTimes\">{{cite news | url=http://well.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/08/09/coca-cola-funds-scientists-who-shift-blame-for-obesity-away-from-bad-diets/?ref=business&_r=0 | title=Coca-Cola Funds Scientists Who Shift Blame for Obesity Away From Bad Diets | work=New York Times | date=August 9, 2015 | accessdate=October 11, 2015}}</ref><ref name=NYT_spending>https://well.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/09/28/coke-spends-lavishly-on-pediatricians-and-dietitians/</ref> It has been criticised by nutrition experts for downplaying the role of junk food in obesity.<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/aug/11/obesity-junk-food-exercise-global-energy-balance-network-coca-cola | title=Nutrition experts alarmed by nonprofit downplaying role of junk food in obesity | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=August 11, 2015 | accessdate=October 11, 2015}}</ref> Critics have also accused the [[American College of Sports Medicine]] (ACSM) of supporting GEBN.<ref>{{Cite web|title = \"Global Energy Balance Network\" is Dead: \"Exercise is Medicine,\" You're Next.|url = http://therussells.crossfit.com/2015/12/02/global-energy-balance-network-is-dead-exercise-is-medicine-youre-next/|website = THE RUSSELLS|access-date = 2016-01-15}}</ref> The ACSM claims it had no affiliation with GEBN.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.acsm.org/about-acsm/media-room/for-the-record |title=For the Record |website=ACSM.com |publisher=American College of Sports Medicine |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310043738/https://www.acsm.org/about-acsm/media-room/for-the-record |archive-date=March 10, 2016 |access-date=January 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nGEBN's view of weight and metabolic health promoted the idea that weight loss can be achieved by taking more exercise while maintaining the same<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://well.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/11/24/cokes-chief-scientist-who-orchestrated-obesity-research-is-leaving/|title=Coke's Chief Scientist, Who Orchestrated Obesity Research, Is Leaving|last=O'Connor|first=Anahad|newspaper=Well|access-date=2016-12-09}}</ref> level of consumption<ref name=\"WaPo\">{{cite web | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonkblog/wp/2015/08/11/the-worlds-largest-seller-of-sugary-drinks-is-telling-people-how-to-lose-weight/ | title=We don\u2019t need to drink less soda, according to research funded by Coca-Cola | publisher=[[Washington Post]] | date=August 11, 2015 | accessdate=October 11, 2015}}</ref> - this view \"crosses a line by advancing a view that falls outside the scientific consensus\", and presents an overly simplistic view of the energy balance equation, with experts noting that \"evidence for eating less as a weight-loss strategy is much, much stronger than the evidence for moving more\".<ref name=\"Healthline\">{{cite web | url=http://www.healthline.com/health-news/why-coca-colas-funding-of-obesity-research-crossed-the-line-081115#3 | title=Why Coca-Cola\u2019s Funding of Obesity Research Crossed the Line | publisher=HealthLine | date=August 11, 2015 | accessdate=October 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Outcome ==\nCoca-Cola was given a 2015 [[Shonky Award]] by Australian consumer organisation [[Choice (Australian consumer organisation)|Choice]], due to its funding of GEBN,<ref name=\"SMHShonky\">{{cite news | url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/retail/samsung-ikea-cocacola-nab-and-kleenex-head-list-of-choice-shonky-award-winners-for-2015-20151006-gk2wgj.html | title=Samsung, Ikea, Coca-Cola, NAB and Kleenex head list of Choice Shonky Award winners for 2015 | work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]] | date=October 7, 2015 | accessdate=October 11, 2015}}</ref> which amounted to at least $1.5m in 2015.<ref name=\"NYTimes\" />\n\nOn November 30, 2015, the group announced on its website that it would discontinue operations immediately.<ref>{{cite news |title=Anti-obesity group funded by Coke disbanding |agency=CBS News/AP |date=December 1, 2015 |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/anti-obesity-group-funded-by-coke-global-energy-balance-network-disbanding/ |accessdate=December 1, 2015}}</ref> Shortly before this, the chief public scientist at [[Coca-Cola]] announced her retirement.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://well.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/11/24/cokes-chief-scientist-who-orchestrated-obesity-research-is-leaving/|title=Coke's Chief Scientist, Who Orchestrated Obesity Research, Is Leaving|last=O'Connor|first=Anahad|newspaper=Well|access-date=2016-12-09}}</ref> Coca-Cola did not replace the position.\n\nOn August 2nd, 2016, it was announced Gregory Hand would be forced out as the Founding Dean of the [[West Virginia University]] School of Public Health.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.corporatecrimereporter.com/news/200/gregory-hand-forced-out-as-dean-of-west-virginia-school-of-public-health-amid-controversy-over-coca-cola-funding/|title=Gregory Hand Forced Out As Dean of West Virginia School of Public Health Amid Controversy Over Coca-Cola Funding - Corporate Crime Reporter|date=2016-08-02|newspaper=Corporate Crime Reporter|language=en-US|access-date=2016-12-09}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 2020, a simplified German-language version of the website is up.<ref name=\"GBNcurrent\">{{cite web |title=Global Balance Network |url=https://gebn.org/ |website=Global Balance Network |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://gebn.org/ Official website] \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20151009014252/https://gebn.org/ Archive of GEBN Website as it existed prior to November 2015]\n\n[[Category:Obesity organizations]]\n[[Category:Coca-Cola]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2014]]\n[[Category:Organizations disestablished in 2015]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox organization\n| logo =\n| extinction = {{End date|November 30, 2015}}\n| type =non profit\n| purpose = front group for Coca-Cola <ref name=NYT><!-- excerpt=\u201cThe Global Energy Balance Network is nothing but a front group for Coca-Cola.\" - M. Nestle  -->http://well.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/08/09/coca-cola-funds-scientists-who-shift-blame-for-obesity-away-from-bad-diets/?_r=2</ref>\n| leader_title  = President<ref name=NYT />\n| leader_name   = [[James O. Hill]]\n| leader_title2 = Founder & Vice-President <ref name=NYT />\n| leader_name2  = [[Steven N. Blair]]\n| leader_name3  = [[Gregory A. Hand]]\n| leader_title3 = Founder<ref name=NYT />\n| name = Global Energy Balance Network\n| founded = {{Start date and age|2014}} at the [[University of Colorado]] and [[University of South Carolina]]\n| products = obesity research\n| owner = [[Coca-Cola]]\n| website = {{URL|gebn.org}} (was registered to Coca-Cola headquarters in Atlanta)<ref name=NYT />\n}}\nThe '''Global Energy Balance Network''' ('''GEBN''') was a US-based nonprofit claiming to fund research into causes of obesity, but was primarily known for promoting the idea that lack of exercise, not bad diet, was primarily responsible for the obesity epidemic. It has been characterised as an [[astroturfing]]<ref name=\"ChoiceFrontGroups\">{{cite web | url=https://www.choice.com.au/shopping/packaging-labelling-and-advertising/advertising/articles/front-groups-and-astroturfing | title=Front groups and 'astroturfing' | publisher=[[Choice (Australian consumer organisation)|Choice]] | accessdate=October 11, 2015}}</ref> organisation. It received substantial funding from [[Coca-Cola]].<ref name=\"NYTimes\">{{cite news | url=http://well.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/08/09/coca-cola-funds-scientists-who-shift-blame-for-obesity-away-from-bad-diets/?ref=business&_r=0 | title=Coca-Cola Funds Scientists Who Shift Blame for Obesity Away From Bad Diets | work=New York Times | date=August 9, 2015 | accessdate=October 11, 2015}}</ref><ref name=NYT_spending>https://well.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/09/28/coke-spends-lavishly-on-pediatricians-and-dietitians/</ref> It has been criticised by nutrition experts for downplaying the role of junk food in obesity.<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/aug/11/obesity-junk-food-exercise-global-energy-balance-network-coca-cola | title=Nutrition experts alarmed by nonprofit downplaying role of junk food in obesity | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=August 11, 2015 | accessdate=October 11, 2015}}</ref> Critics have also accused the [[American College of Sports Medicine]] (ACSM) of supporting GEBN.<ref>{{Cite web|title = \"Global Energy Balance Network\" is Dead: \"Exercise is Medicine,\" You're Next.|url = http://therussells.crossfit.com/2015/12/02/global-energy-balance-network-is-dead-exercise-is-medicine-youre-next/|website = THE RUSSELLS|access-date = 2016-01-15}}</ref> The ACSM claims it had no affiliation with GEBN.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.acsm.org/about-acsm/media-room/for-the-record |title=For the Record |website=ACSM.com |publisher=American College of Sports Medicine |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310043738/https://www.acsm.org/about-acsm/media-room/for-the-record |archive-date=March 10, 2016 |access-date=January 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nGEBN's view of weight and metabolic health promoted the idea that weight loss can be achieved by taking more exercise while maintaining the same<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://well.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/11/24/cokes-chief-scientist-who-orchestrated-obesity-research-is-leaving/|title=Coke's Chief Scientist, Who Orchestrated Obesity Research, Is Leaving|last=O'Connor|first=Anahad|newspaper=Well|access-date=2016-12-09}}</ref> level of consumption<ref name=\"WaPo\">{{cite web | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonkblog/wp/2015/08/11/the-worlds-largest-seller-of-sugary-drinks-is-telling-people-how-to-lose-weight/ | title=We don\u2019t need to drink less soda, according to research funded by Coca-Cola | publisher=[[Washington Post]] | date=August 11, 2015 | accessdate=October 11, 2015}}</ref> - this view \"crosses a line by advancing a view that falls outside the scientific consensus\", and presents an overly simplistic view of the energy balance equation, with experts noting that \"evidence for eating less as a weight-loss strategy is much, much stronger than the evidence for moving more\".<ref name=\"Healthline\">{{cite web | url=http://www.healthline.com/health-news/why-coca-colas-funding-of-obesity-research-crossed-the-line-081115#3 | title=Why Coca-Cola\u2019s Funding of Obesity Research Crossed the Line | publisher=HealthLine | date=August 11, 2015 | accessdate=October 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Outcome ==\nCoca-Cola was given a 2015 \"Shonky Award\" by Australian consumer organisation [[Choice (Australian consumer organisation)|Choice]], due to its funding of GEBN,<ref name=\"SMHShonky\">{{cite news | url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/retail/samsung-ikea-cocacola-nab-and-kleenex-head-list-of-choice-shonky-award-winners-for-2015-20151006-gk2wgj.html | title=Samsung, Ikea, Coca-Cola, NAB and Kleenex head list of Choice Shonky Award winners for 2015 | work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]] | date=October 7, 2015 | accessdate=October 11, 2015}}</ref> which amounted to at least $1.5m in 2015.<ref name=\"NYTimes\" />\n\nOn November 30, 2015, the group announced on its website that it would discontinue operations immediately.<ref>{{cite news |title=Anti-obesity group funded by Coke disbanding |agency=CBS News/AP |date=December 1, 2015 |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/anti-obesity-group-funded-by-coke-global-energy-balance-network-disbanding/ |accessdate=December 1, 2015}}</ref> Shortly before this, the chief public scientist at [[Coca-Cola]] announced her retirement.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://well.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/11/24/cokes-chief-scientist-who-orchestrated-obesity-research-is-leaving/|title=Coke's Chief Scientist, Who Orchestrated Obesity Research, Is Leaving|last=O'Connor|first=Anahad|newspaper=Well|access-date=2016-12-09}}</ref> Coca-Cola did not replace the position.\n\nOn August 2nd, 2016, it was announced Gregory Hand would be forced out as the Founding Dean of the [[West Virginia University]] School of Public Health.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.corporatecrimereporter.com/news/200/gregory-hand-forced-out-as-dean-of-west-virginia-school-of-public-health-amid-controversy-over-coca-cola-funding/|title=Gregory Hand Forced Out As Dean of West Virginia School of Public Health Amid Controversy Over 